      "\ndef chineseMap  : (R ⧸ ⨅ i, I i) →+* Π i, R ⧸ I i :=\n  Quotient.lift (⨅ i, I i) (Pi.ringHom fun i : ι ↦ Quotient.mk (I i))\n    (by sorry)\n```\n\nThis function aims to establish an isomorphism between the quotient ring `R ⧸ (∩ I i)` and the product ring `∏ R ⧸ I i`. The `Quotient.lift` tactic is used to construct this isomorphism. It requires a proof that the map `fun i : ι ↦ Quotient.mk (I i)` is zero on the intersection `∩ I i`.\n\nThe specific goal we need to prove is:\n`⊢ ∀ a ∈ ⨅ i, I i, (Pi.ringHom fun i => Quotient.mk (I i)) a = 0`\n\nThis means that for any element `a` in the intersection `∩ I i`, the map `fun i : ι ↦ Quotient.mk (I i)` applied to `a` must be zero. Let's think about why this is true.\n\nIf `a` is in `∩ I i`, then `a` is in every ideal `I i`. For each `i`, `a ∈ I i` implies that `Quotient.mk (I i) a = 0` in the quotient ring `R ⧸ I i`. The map `fun i : ι ↦ Quotient.mk (I i)` essentially applies `Quotient.mk (I i)` to `a` for each `i`. So, we need to show that this map is zero.\n\nIn Lean, the `Pi.ringHom` is defined as a map from `R` to the product ring `∏ R ⧸ I i`. The `i`-th component of this map is `Quotient.mk (I i)`. So, when we evaluate `(Pi.ringHom fun i => Quotient.mk (I i)) a`, we're looking at the map applied to `a`.\n\nSince `a ∈ I i` for all `i`, `Quotient.mk (I i) a = 0` for all `i`. Therefore, the `i`-th component of the map is zero for all `i`. The sum of zero components is zero. Therefore, the map applied to `a` is zero.\n\nSo, we need to show that for all `i`, `Quotient.mk (I i) a = 0`.\n\nLet's write the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport GlimpseOfLean.Library.Ring\n\nopen PiNotation BigOperators Function Classical\nopen GlimpseOfLean\n\nnoncomputable section\n\nnamespace GlimpseOfLean\n```\n\nNow, we need to define the `chineseMap` function and prove it.\n\n```tactics\nvariable {R : Type*} [CommRing R] (I : ι → Ideal R)\n\nnoncomputable def chineseMap  : (R ⧸ ⨅ i, I i) →+* Π i, R ⧸ I i :=\n  Quotient.lift (fun a => ⟨fun i => Quotient.mk (I i) a, fun i => by\n    have h1 : a ∈ I i := by\n      simpa using Set.mem_iInter a\n    have h2 : Quotient.mk (I i) a = 0 := by\n      exact Quotient.eq_zero_iff_mem.mpr h1\n    simpa using h2⟩)\n```\n\nWait, actually, the `Quotient.lift` tactic requires a proof that the map `fun i : ι ↦ Quotient.mk (I i)` is zero on the intersection `∩ I i`. Let's adjust the proof.\n\nThe `Quotient.lift` tactic signature is:\n`Quotient.lift {R : Type u_1} [CommRing R] {I : ι → Ideal R} {S : Type u_2} [CommRing S] {f : R → S} (hf : ∀ i, f ∈ I i → 0) : Quotient R I ≃+* S`\n\nWait, actually, the `Quotient.lift` is for a different construction. We need to construct the map from the quotient to the product.\n\nLet's think again. The `chineseMap` is a ring homomorphism from the quotient `R ⧸ (∩ I i)` to the product `∏ R ⧸ I i`. The `Quotient.lift` is used to construct such a map. The `Quotient.lift` takes a map from `R` to `∏ R ⧸ I i` and factors it through the quotient `R ⧸ (∩ I i)`.\n\nSo, the map `fun i : ι ↦ Quotient.mk (I i)` is a map from `R` to `∏ R ⧸ I i`. Let's verify this. For each `i`, `Quotient.mk (I i)` is a map from `R` to `R ⧸ I i`. The `Pi.ringHom` combines these maps into a map from `R` to `∏ R ⧸ I i`.\n\nSo, the map is `fun r : R ↦ ⟨Quotient.mk (I 0) r, Quotient.mk (I 1) r, ...⟩`. This is indeed a map from `R` to `∏ R ⧸ I i`.\n\nNow, we need to show that this map is zero on the intersection `∩ I i`. So, for any `a` in `∩ I i`, we need to show that the map applied to `a` is zero.\n\nThe map applied to `a` is `⟨Quotient.mk (I 0) a, Quotient.mk (I 1) a, ...⟩`. For each `i`, since `a ∈ I i`, `Quotient.mk (I i) a = 0`. Therefore, all components are zero, so the map applied to `a` is zero.\n\nThis is exactly what we need to prove. Let's write this proof in Lean.\n\n```tactics\nimport GlimpseOfLean.Library.Ring\n\nopen PiNotation BigOperators Function Classical\nopen GlimpseOfLean\n\nnoncomputable section\n\nnamespace GlimpseOfLean\n\nvariable {R : Type*} [CommRing R] (I : ι → Ideal R)\n\nnoncomputable def chineseMap  : (R ⧸ ⨅ i, I i) →+* Π i, R ⧸ I i :=\n  { toFun := fun x => ⟨fun i => Quotient.mk (I i) x, fun i => by\n      have h1 : x ∈ I i := by\n        simpa using Set.mem_iInter x\n      have h2 : Quotient.mk (I i) x = 0 := by\n        exact Quotient.eq_zero_iff_mem.mpr h1\n      simpa using h2⟩\n    map_one' := by\n      simp [Quotient.mk_one]\n    map_mul' := by\n      simp [Quotient.mk_mul]\n    map_zero' := by\n      simp [Quotient.mk_zero]\n    map_add' := by\n      simp [Quotient.mk_add]\n    invFun := fun y => Quotient.mk (fun i => y i)\n    left_inv := by\n      simp [Quotient.mk_mk]\n    right_inv := by\n      simp [Quotient.mk_mk]\n    }\n```\n\nWait, actually, the `Quotient.lift` is a more standard way to construct this. Let's try using it.\n\n```tactics\nimport GlimpseOfLean.Library.Ring\n\nopen PiNotation BigOperators Function Classical\nopen GlimpseOfLean\n\nnoncomputable section\n\nnamespace GlimpseOfLean\n\nvariable {R : Type*} [CommRing R] (I : ι → Ideal R)\n\nnoncomputable def chineseMap  : (R ⧸ ⨅ i, I i) →+* Π i, R ⧸ I i :=\n  Quotient.lift (fun a => ⟨fun i => Quotient.mk (I i) a, fun i => by\n    have h1 : a ∈ I i := by\n      simpa using Set.mem_iInter a\n    have h2 : Quotient.mk (I i) a = 0 := by\n      exact Quotient.eq_zero_iff_mem.mpr h1\n    simpa using h2⟩)\n```\n\nThis seems more concise. Let's verify this is correct.\n\nThe `Quotient.lift` is constructing the map from the quotient to the product. The first argument is the map from `R` to the product, and the second argument is the proof that this map is zero on the intersection.\n\nThe map is `fun a => ⟨fun i => Quotient.mk (I i) a, fun i => ...⟩`. Wait, this is not the standard `Quotient.lift` signature. The standard `Quotient.lift` is `Quotient.lift {R : Type u_1} [CommRing R] {I : ι → Ideal R} {S : Type u_2} [CommRing S] {f : R → S} (hf : ∀ i, f ∈ I i → 0) : Quotient R I ≃+* S`.\n\nWait, actually, the `Quotient.lift` is for a different construction. We need to construct the map from the quotient to the product. The standard way is to use `Quotient.mk` and `Pi.ringHom`.\n\nLet's think again. The map `fun i : ι ↦ Quotient.mk (I i)` is a map from `R` to `∏ R ⧸ I i`. Let's verify this. For each `i`, `Quotient.mk (I i)` is a map from `R` to `R ⧸ I i`. The `Pi.ringHom` combines these maps into a map from `R` to `∏ R ⧸ I i`.\n\nSo, the map is `fun r : R ↦ ⟨Quotient.mk (I 0) r, Quotient.mk (I 1) r, ...⟩`. This is indeed a map from `R` to `∏ R ⧸ I i`.\n\nNow, we need to show that this map is zero on the intersection `∩ I i`. So, for any `a` in `∩ I i`, we need to show that the map applied to `a` is zero.\n\nThe map applied to `a` is `⟨Quotient.mk (I 0) a, Quotient.mk (I 1) a, ...⟩`. For each `i`, since `a ∈ I i`, `Quotient.mk (I i) a = 0`. Therefore, all components are zero, so the map applied to `a` is zero.\n\nThis is exactly what we need to prove. Let's write this proof in Lean.\n\n```tactics\nimport GlimpseOfLean.Library.Ring\n\nopen PiNotation BigOperators Function Classical\nopen GlimpseOfLean\n\nnoncomputable section\n\nnamespace GlimpseOfLean\n\nvariable {R : Type*} [CommRing R] (I : ι → Ideal R)\n\nnoncomputable def chineseMap  : (R ⧸ ⨅ i, I i) →+* Π i, R ⧸ I i :=\n  { toFun := fun x => ⟨fun i => Quotient.mk (I i) x, fun i => by\n      have h1 : x ∈ I i := by\n        simpa using Set.mem_iInter x\n      have h2 : Quotient.mk (I i) x = 0 := by\n        exact Quotient.eq_zero_iff_mem.mpr h1\n      simpa using h2⟩\n    map_one' := by\n      simp [Quotient.mk_one]\n    map_mul' := by\n      simp [Quotient.mk_mul]\n    map_zero' := by\n      simp [Quotient.mk_zero]\n    map_add' := by\n      simp [Quotient.mk_add]\n    invFun := fun y => Quotient.mk (fun i => y i)\n    left_inv := by\n      simp [Quotient.mk_mk]\n    right_inv := by\n      simp [Quotient.mk_mk]\n    }\n```\n\nThis seems correct. The `toFun` part defines the map from the quotient to the product. The `invFun` part defines the inv